'''Aliunde''' is [[Latin]] for "from another place" and is related to the word "alibi" (Latin for "elsewhere").  The Latin word for "whence" (from where) is ''unde'' and together with ''alius'' becomes ''aliunde'' - from another source, or place.

For instance, in the description of a river's source, the headwaters are usually attributed to one place, but if, for instance, an administrative body investigates the matter and determines that water is coming from somewhere else, the adverb they might use to describe this other source (Latin ''fons'' - a [[Spring (water)|spring]]) would be "aliunde" &mdash; from somewhere else.

